WEBVTT

00:02.336 --> 00:04.737
A famous queen throws
a $1 million dinner...

00:04.739 --> 00:06.538
ZENON: She's the most powerful
woman in the world,

00:06.540 --> 00:08.540
but if this goes wrong,
that's it.

00:08.542 --> 00:10.008
She's only got one shot at it.

00:11.912 --> 00:15.180
...a corny trick
to outsmart the British...

00:15.182 --> 00:17.649
DiPAOLO: Buildings were burning.
Shots were being fired.

00:17.651 --> 00:19.351
It was a terrifying place to be.

00:21.154 --> 00:25.690
...and a long-lost shipwreck
unlocks a cinematic mystery.

00:25.692 --> 00:28.994
He is this literary icon,
this larger-than-life character.

00:28.996 --> 00:31.196
♪♪

00:31.198 --> 00:33.699
These are the mysteries
at the museum.

00:33.701 --> 00:39.437
♪♪

00:39.439 --> 00:42.775
The Netherlands is famous
for its elegant windmills,

00:42.777 --> 00:44.609
massive dykes,

00:44.611 --> 00:46.845
and colorful tulips.

00:46.847 --> 00:50.382
Each spring, more than 7 million
of these flowers bloom

00:50.384 --> 00:53.151
in this Dutch nation's most
famous garden,

00:53.153 --> 00:54.520
the Keukenhof.

00:54.522 --> 00:58.523
It's the largest
tulip collection in the world.

00:58.525 --> 01:00.392
But a different kind of beauty
can be found

01:00.394 --> 01:04.530
in the capital city
of Amsterdam,

01:04.532 --> 01:06.598
at the Rijksmuseum.

01:06.600 --> 01:10.335
♪♪

01:10.337 --> 01:12.737
The collection includes

01:12.739 --> 01:14.206
an 18th-century cabinet

01:14.208 --> 01:17.810
covered in a copper
and tortoise shell veneer,

01:17.812 --> 01:22.747
an elaborate model of
a 17th-century Dutch warship,

01:22.749 --> 01:26.150
and a violin
dating back to 1705.

01:26.152 --> 01:31.423
♪♪

01:31.425 --> 01:34.893
But one item here stands apart.

01:34.895 --> 01:38.297
It's about 12 inches high
by 18 inches wide.

01:38.299 --> 01:40.932
It's in a gilded wooden frame.

01:40.934 --> 01:42.834
Even though the painting
is quite old,

01:42.836 --> 01:46.004
the colors are really vibrant.

01:46.006 --> 01:48.707
WILDMAN: This painting depicts
one of the most famous rulers

01:48.709 --> 01:50.909
of the ancient world,

01:50.911 --> 01:52.711
and it recalls the daring stunt

01:52.713 --> 01:56.714
that catapulted her into
the history books forever.

01:56.716 --> 01:59.250
ZENON: This picture depicts
a real-life feast

01:59.252 --> 02:01.453
that history would never forget.

02:01.455 --> 02:07.125
♪♪

02:07.127 --> 02:11.029
WILDMAN:
The story begins in 33 B.C.

02:11.031 --> 02:12.464
Egypt is ruled by

02:12.466 --> 02:16.168
the all-powerful
queen of the Nile, Cleopatra.

02:16.170 --> 02:17.602
ZENON: Queen Cleopatra is

02:17.604 --> 02:19.204
the most powerful woman
in the world.

02:19.206 --> 02:21.373
She's smart. She's beautiful.

02:21.375 --> 02:23.909
And Cleopatra, being Cleopatra,

02:23.911 --> 02:25.910
she's got everybody
at her beck and command.

02:25.912 --> 02:28.347
She can basically get
pretty much anything she wants.

02:28.349 --> 02:33.018
♪♪

02:33.020 --> 02:34.286
WILDMAN: But there is one thing

02:34.288 --> 02:37.055
that power and money
cannot buy --

02:37.057 --> 02:38.490
love.

02:38.492 --> 02:41.293
The magnificent queen
has her heart set on winning

02:41.295 --> 02:46.031
the affections of the powerful
Roman general Marc Antony.

02:46.033 --> 02:49.101
As the story goes,
she sets out to woo him

02:49.103 --> 02:52.037
by staging an elaborate
dinner party.

02:52.039 --> 02:54.806
She promises it will be
the most expensive feast

02:54.808 --> 02:59.477
ever thrown, at a cost
of 10 million sesterces.

02:59.479 --> 03:03.649
ZENON: This is probably around
about $100 million these days,

03:03.651 --> 03:06.251
so this is a ridiculous amount
of money.

03:06.253 --> 03:09.587
♪♪

03:09.589 --> 03:11.323
WILDMAN: Cleopatra invites
Marc Antony

03:11.325 --> 03:13.592
to her most lavish banquet hall

03:13.594 --> 03:16.528
and unveils the first course.

03:16.530 --> 03:18.997
ZENON: The setting
is completely opulent.

03:18.999 --> 03:20.666
Anybody who is anybody is there.

03:20.668 --> 03:22.934
And then the food starts
to arrive,

03:22.936 --> 03:25.504
and it is really impressive.

03:25.506 --> 03:28.340
WILDMAN: But the general is not
so easily awed.

03:28.342 --> 03:32.277
He's accustomed to a life
of luxury back in Rome.

03:32.279 --> 03:34.479
ZENON: Probably at this point,
Antony is thinking,

03:34.481 --> 03:36.415
"This is great, but it's not
$100 million worth."

03:36.417 --> 03:39.751
♪♪

03:39.753 --> 03:42.621
WILDMAN: Not one to be deterred,

03:42.623 --> 03:46.524
the cunning queen summons
the next course.

03:46.526 --> 03:49.160
But instead
of a plentiful plate of food,

03:49.162 --> 03:53.464
a servant brings out
a small cup of vinegar.

03:53.466 --> 03:57.502
Then Cleopatra removes
a massive pearl from her ear

03:57.504 --> 04:00.105
and shows it to Marc Antony.

04:00.107 --> 04:02.307
ZENON: Now this wasn't just
any pearl earring.

04:02.309 --> 04:06.177
This was the largest pearl
the world had ever known.

04:06.179 --> 04:08.113
In those days,
it was a very rare

04:08.115 --> 04:13.352
and a very precious item that
could be worth $100 million.

04:13.354 --> 04:15.187
WILDMAN: Cleopatra drops
the pearl

04:15.189 --> 04:16.721
into the cup of vinegar.

04:16.723 --> 04:19.925
♪♪

04:19.927 --> 04:24.196
Moments later,
the pearl dissolves.

04:24.198 --> 04:27.999
It's then that she plays
her master stroke.

04:28.001 --> 04:32.270
She drinks
the extravagant cocktail.

04:32.272 --> 04:35.140
Marc Antony is astonished.

04:35.142 --> 04:37.275
ZENON: It must have been
quite amazing.

04:37.277 --> 04:39.544
It was showmanship in action.

04:39.546 --> 04:40.945
WILDMAN:
According to the story,

04:40.947 --> 04:43.081
the Roman general is
so impressed

04:43.083 --> 04:45.083
that he falls for
the Egyptian queen,

04:45.085 --> 04:48.086
and the two embark
on a passionate affair.

04:48.088 --> 04:49.955
ZENON: Their romance
has always been considered

04:49.957 --> 04:51.623
one of the most famous
in history,

04:51.625 --> 04:54.359
and it's stayed in the world's
imagination ever since.

04:54.361 --> 04:57.796
♪♪

04:57.798 --> 05:00.565
WILDMAN: But while the tale
itself is a captivating one,

05:00.567 --> 05:04.569
many modern historians wonder
if it's actually true.

05:04.571 --> 05:07.639
Can a pearl be dissolved
in vinegar?

05:07.641 --> 05:09.507
ZENON: This is kind of
a classic legend, really.

05:09.509 --> 05:11.176
Did it happen or didn't it?

05:11.178 --> 05:14.579
WILDMAN: So what's the truth
behind this $1 million dinner?

05:14.581 --> 05:19.584
♪♪

05:19.586 --> 05:23.055
It's 1957.

05:23.057 --> 05:25.123
A professor
named Berthold Ullman,

05:25.125 --> 05:26.858
the chair of
the classic department

05:26.860 --> 05:28.927
at the University
of North Carolina,

05:28.929 --> 05:32.097
sets out to solve the mystery
once and for all.

05:33.600 --> 05:35.066
ZENON: Curious about this.

05:35.068 --> 05:36.667
This is the story of how
the world lost

05:36.669 --> 05:37.936
its largest pearl.

05:37.938 --> 05:41.440
♪♪

05:41.442 --> 05:44.209
WILDMAN:
With help from the university's
chemistry department,

05:44.211 --> 05:46.678
Ullman learns that it<i> is</i>
possible for pearls

05:46.680 --> 05:48.880
to be broken down by vinegar.

05:48.882 --> 05:52.417
You're talking about vinegar
being essentially acetic acid,

05:52.419 --> 05:55.820
and you talk about a pearl
being calcium carbonate.

05:55.822 --> 05:57.221
One will dissolve the other.

05:57.223 --> 05:58.990
It's just a question
of how quickly.

06:01.095 --> 06:04.296
WILDMAN:
So Ullman sets up an experiment.

06:04.298 --> 06:06.298
He fills a glass
with acetic acid

06:06.300 --> 06:11.069
that equals the acidity
of the vinegar of ancient Egypt.

06:11.071 --> 06:15.841
Then he drops a pearl
into the solution.

06:15.843 --> 06:20.746
As time passes,
something strange happens.

06:20.748 --> 06:26.184
He can see that the pearl seems
to be dissolving in the cup.

06:26.186 --> 06:30.121
It's finally all dissolved away.

06:30.123 --> 06:32.857
It seems to have worked.

06:32.859 --> 06:35.059
WILDMAN: The process
to make the pearl disappear

06:35.061 --> 06:37.128
takes several hours.

06:37.130 --> 06:38.797
But upon further testing,

06:38.799 --> 06:41.199
Ullman learns that
the dissolution process

06:41.201 --> 06:42.467
can be sped up

06:42.469 --> 06:46.238
by boiling the vinegar
or crushing the pearl.

06:46.240 --> 06:48.406
The mystery is solved.

06:48.408 --> 06:49.941
The interesting thing is,
it's a legend

06:49.943 --> 06:52.911
that could be based on facts
after all.

06:52.913 --> 06:54.346
♪♪

06:54.348 --> 06:57.716
WILDMAN: Today, a depiction
of Cleopatra's famous gambit,

06:57.718 --> 07:00.418
painted by Dutch master
Gerard de Lairesse,

07:00.420 --> 07:04.689
is on display at the Rijksmuseum
in Amsterdam.

07:04.691 --> 07:08.827
It recalls a lavish concoction
fit for a queen.

07:12.566 --> 07:13.832
♪♪

07:13.834 --> 07:15.567
Albuquerque, New Mexico,

07:15.569 --> 07:17.903
is home to one of the oldest
Catholic churches

07:17.905 --> 07:19.937
in the United States,

07:19.939 --> 07:22.373
San Felipe de Neri.

07:22.375 --> 07:25.977
First built by Spanish colonists
in 1706,

07:25.979 --> 07:29.948
today, the building is known for
its prominent twin bell towers,

07:29.950 --> 07:32.016
5-foot-thick adobe walls,

07:32.018 --> 07:34.952
and Gothic revival architecture.

07:34.954 --> 07:36.922
And not far from
this historic structure

07:36.924 --> 07:39.691
is a more modern institution --

07:39.693 --> 07:43.595
the Anderson-Abruzzo Albuquerque
International Balloon Museum.

07:43.597 --> 07:47.465
♪♪

07:47.467 --> 07:51.002
On display is a model of
the first ever manned balloon,

07:51.004 --> 07:53.104
Le Reveillon,

07:53.106 --> 07:55.807
a replica of a 1999 gondola

07:55.809 --> 08:00.278
that completed the first
nonstop round-the-world flight,

08:00.280 --> 08:02.547
and a model of
the Graf Zeppelin,

08:02.549 --> 08:05.217
which, in 1928,
became the first aircraft

08:05.219 --> 08:06.818
to offer commercial flights

08:06.820 --> 08:08.920
across the Atlantic Ocean.

08:08.922 --> 08:13.824
♪♪

08:13.826 --> 08:17.094
But one artifact here seems to
have no obvious connection

08:17.096 --> 08:19.864
to lighter than air flight
at all.

08:19.866 --> 08:21.967
REIDY: The object is about
20 inches long

08:21.969 --> 08:23.768
and 15 inches wide.

08:23.770 --> 08:28.006
It's comprised of glass,
metal, and plastic pieces.

08:28.008 --> 08:30.575
It looks like the guts
of a piece of machinery.

08:30.577 --> 08:32.711
♪♪

08:32.713 --> 08:35.847
WILDMAN: This strange device
recalls the puzzling tale

08:35.849 --> 08:37.382
of a curious farmer

08:37.384 --> 08:40.552
and a seemingly sinister
military cover-up.

08:40.554 --> 08:44.588
The artifact is connected to one
family's pursuit of the truth

08:44.590 --> 08:46.791
in the face of
government conspiracy.

08:46.793 --> 08:51.128
♪♪

08:51.130 --> 08:53.665
WILDMAN: It's 1962.

08:53.667 --> 08:57.335
David McPherson lives with his
wife and son on a remote farm

08:57.337 --> 09:00.171
in the Canadian province
of New Brunswick.

09:00.173 --> 09:03.407
McPherson lived a quiet life
with his family.

09:03.409 --> 09:04.776
He lived off the land.

09:04.778 --> 09:06.144
He knew it like
the back of his hand.

09:06.146 --> 09:10.081
♪♪

09:10.083 --> 09:13.084
WILDMAN: One day, McPherson
is gathering timber in the woods

09:13.086 --> 09:17.221
when he spots something unusual.

09:17.223 --> 09:21.426
Tangled in a tree is a strange
swath of billowing fabric

09:21.428 --> 09:25.430
with long ropes that
dangle down to the ground.

09:25.432 --> 09:28.432
It appears to be a parachute.

09:28.434 --> 09:30.101
Beneath it on the ground,

09:30.103 --> 09:33.638
McPherson finds
a large white box,

09:33.640 --> 09:37.776
but it's unlike any kind of box
he's seen before.

09:37.778 --> 09:41.312
It was made of some hard,
metallic substance.

09:41.314 --> 09:43.248
The front and the bottom
of the object

09:43.250 --> 09:45.917
had two small glass panes,

09:45.919 --> 09:48.720
but he couldn't quite see
through them.

09:48.722 --> 09:52.924
WILDMAN: The box has no
identifying words or markings.

09:52.926 --> 09:56.528
McPherson is intrigued
and begins to wonder what is

09:56.530 --> 09:58.329
and where it could've come from.

09:58.331 --> 09:59.630
He had to get
to the bottom of it.

09:59.632 --> 10:01.800
He was totally captivated.

10:04.338 --> 10:08.540
So the farmer drags
the heavy box back to his barn,

10:08.542 --> 10:10.108
where he begins
searching for clues

10:10.110 --> 10:12.944
about its contents or purpose.

10:12.946 --> 10:15.680
But try as he might, he fails.

10:15.682 --> 10:18.315
REIDY: He tried his hardest
to open the box,

10:18.317 --> 10:21.686
but whatever tools he used,
it wouldn't budge.

10:21.688 --> 10:26.224
It was sealed shut
no matter what he did.

10:26.226 --> 10:28.126
WILDMAN: McPherson gives
the enigmatic box

10:28.128 --> 10:29.961
a simple nickname.

10:29.963 --> 10:33.831
He started referring to this as
the "thing in the woods."

10:33.833 --> 10:36.100
♪♪

10:36.102 --> 10:39.704
WILDMAN: Then, just days after
his extraordinary discovery,

10:39.706 --> 10:42.407
McPherson is visited by two men.

10:42.409 --> 10:45.310
They claim to be members
of the Canadian military,

10:45.312 --> 10:48.913
and they tell McPherson
that they have come for the box.

10:48.915 --> 10:51.716
REIDY: At that moment,
he knew this was serious

10:51.718 --> 10:54.685
and much bigger than him.

10:54.687 --> 10:56.053
WILDMAN:
With little explanation,

10:56.055 --> 10:58.823
the soldiers confiscate
the strange object,

10:58.825 --> 11:02.260
put it in the back of a truck,
and haul it away.

11:02.262 --> 11:04.729
REIDY: It was very frustrating
for McPherson

11:04.731 --> 11:06.531
to watch this happen.

11:06.533 --> 11:08.933
Now he might never discover
the truth behind

11:08.935 --> 11:10.402
the thing in the woods.

11:10.404 --> 11:14.339
♪♪

11:14.341 --> 11:17.008
WILDMAN: McPherson petitions
the Canadian government

11:17.010 --> 11:21.011
to release information about
the curious cube,

11:21.013 --> 11:23.047
and even though
he never gets a reply,

11:23.049 --> 11:26.184
he keeps making requests
for decades.

11:26.186 --> 11:28.953
He was desperate to figure out
what that thing was

11:28.955 --> 11:31.222
and why they showed up
at his house that day.

11:32.759 --> 11:34.292
WILDMAN: In 2015,

11:34.294 --> 11:38.696
McPherson passes away
without learning the truth.

11:38.698 --> 11:42.300
But his son, David Jr.,
takes up the cause.

11:42.302 --> 11:44.268
REIDY: The mystery
of the thing in the woods

11:44.270 --> 11:46.504
was almost like
a family heirloom.

11:46.506 --> 11:50.107
He wanted to get the answers
that his father never could.

11:50.109 --> 11:51.909
WILDMAN:
So can he crack the case

11:51.911 --> 11:54.345
of the thing in the woods?

11:54.347 --> 11:56.247
♪♪

11:58.168 --> 12:00.168
♪♪

12:00.170 --> 12:04.572
In 1962, a farmer named
David McPherson

12:04.574 --> 12:06.640
found a strange white box

12:06.642 --> 12:09.743
in the woods
of New Brunswick, Canada.

12:09.745 --> 12:11.713
But before he could
figure out what it was,

12:11.715 --> 12:14.649
the military confiscated it.

12:14.651 --> 12:17.986
So what's the truth behind
this confounding crate?

12:17.988 --> 12:21.122
♪♪

12:21.124 --> 12:23.491
For years,
David Jr. continues

12:23.493 --> 12:26.694
to pressure the government
for information.

12:26.696 --> 12:30.531
Then, in 2017,
the CIA declassifies

12:30.533 --> 12:33.534
a trove of
Cold War-related documents.

12:33.536 --> 12:37.639
Among them is a report that
could crack the case wide open.

12:39.175 --> 12:43.611
It details a long-defunct U.S.
military intelligence program,

12:43.613 --> 12:46.247
Project Genetrix.

12:46.249 --> 12:49.884
REIDY: Project Genetrix was
enacted by President Eisenhower

12:49.886 --> 12:52.686
in the 1950s
to secretly spy on

12:52.688 --> 12:55.156
the Soviet Union
and Communist China.

12:55.158 --> 12:56.758
♪♪

12:56.760 --> 12:59.294
WILDMAN: To gather information
on America's enemies,

12:59.296 --> 13:03.498
the military affixed cameras
to special weather balloons.

13:03.500 --> 13:04.732
Riding the jet stream,

13:04.734 --> 13:07.702
these balloons would glide
into enemy territory

13:07.704 --> 13:10.905
at altitudes that made them
nearly undetectable.

13:10.907 --> 13:13.374
The cameras took pictures
of infrastructure,

13:13.376 --> 13:18.446
military installations,
and missile silos below.

13:18.448 --> 13:22.183
According to CIA records,
the camera equipment was housed

13:22.185 --> 13:24.085
in a sealed white box,

13:24.087 --> 13:27.922
just like the one found by
David McPherson on his property.

13:27.924 --> 13:31.125
REIDY: When David McPherson Jr.
learned all of this,

13:31.127 --> 13:32.527
he was totally floored.

13:32.529 --> 13:34.796
It was so much more elaborate
than anything

13:34.798 --> 13:36.798
he or his father thought of.

13:36.800 --> 13:40.268
♪♪

13:40.270 --> 13:42.604
WILDMAN: David Jr. believes
his father found

13:42.606 --> 13:45.506
one of these camera housings
that had blown off course

13:45.508 --> 13:48.476
and crash-landed
near the family farm.

13:48.478 --> 13:51.445
This question that had hung
over his family for decades

13:51.447 --> 13:52.813
was finally answered.

13:52.815 --> 13:56.885
♪♪

13:56.887 --> 13:59.787
WILDMAN: Today, this
Project Genetrix spy camera

13:59.789 --> 14:02.156
is on permanent display at

14:02.158 --> 14:05.426
the Anderson-Abruzzo Albuquerque
International Balloon Museum

14:05.428 --> 14:07.762
in New Mexico.

14:07.764 --> 14:10.498
It provides
an intriguing snapshot

14:10.500 --> 14:13.434
into one family's quest
to uncover the truth.

14:13.436 --> 14:19.907
♪♪

14:19.909 --> 14:21.242
Delaware.

14:21.244 --> 14:24.244
In 1609,
explorer Henry Hudson

14:24.246 --> 14:26.180
first charted the Delaware Bay

14:26.182 --> 14:29.851
while searching for a sea route
from Europe to Asia.

14:29.853 --> 14:32.119
And located on
the Bay's western shore,

14:32.121 --> 14:34.422
in the town of Lewes,

14:34.424 --> 14:38.726
is an institution that charts
the region's rich history,

14:38.728 --> 14:40.895
the Lewes Historical Society.

14:43.600 --> 14:45.299
Among the collection is

14:45.301 --> 14:48.469
an early type of flare gun,

14:48.471 --> 14:51.773
a 19th-century brass compass,

14:51.775 --> 14:56.244
and a diving suit and helmet
dating back to the 1890s.

14:56.246 --> 14:59.480
♪♪

14:59.482 --> 15:02.149
But protruding from
the museum's foundation

15:02.151 --> 15:05.153
is a far more ominous object.

15:05.155 --> 15:08.022
It's stuck inside
of an old brick wall,

15:08.024 --> 15:11.059
and it's made
of a dull black iron.

15:11.061 --> 15:12.627
It's very small,

15:12.629 --> 15:14.829
and only half of it is exposed.

15:14.831 --> 15:17.465
♪♪

15:17.467 --> 15:21.102
WILDMAN: This cannonball has
been lodged in this very spot

15:21.104 --> 15:23.404
for more than 200 years,

15:23.406 --> 15:25.473
and it's linked to
a brilliant plot

15:25.475 --> 15:30.011
to outsmart one of
America's earliest enemies.

15:30.013 --> 15:31.445
DiPAOLO: The item is connected

15:31.447 --> 15:33.714
to a commander's
creativity and cunning

15:33.716 --> 15:35.249
in the face of defeat.

15:35.251 --> 15:41.689
♪♪

15:41.691 --> 15:44.392
WILDMAN: It's 1813.

15:44.394 --> 15:48.396
Just 30 years
after winning independence.

15:48.398 --> 15:50.798
The United States is embroiled
in another war

15:50.800 --> 15:52.133
with Great Britain,

15:52.135 --> 15:55.937
this time over trading
and maritime rights.

15:55.939 --> 15:59.207
The powerful Royal Navy
is sailing from the Chesapeake

15:59.209 --> 16:03.144
to the Delaware Bay, attacking
small towns along the way,

16:03.146 --> 16:05.879
♪♪

16:05.881 --> 16:10.251
and their next target is one of
America's most important port,

16:10.253 --> 16:12.620
Lewes, Delaware.

16:12.622 --> 16:13.821
DiPAOLO: Lewes was one of

16:13.823 --> 16:16.090
the largest agricultural
complexes in the nation,

16:16.092 --> 16:19.627
providing corn, wheat,
tobacco, and cotton

16:19.629 --> 16:22.630
to American enterprises
and businesses abroad.

16:22.632 --> 16:24.965
♪♪

16:24.967 --> 16:27.968
WILDMAN: Charged with defending
this important shipping center

16:27.970 --> 16:30.538
is Colonel Samuel Davis.

16:30.540 --> 16:32.707
DiPAOLO:
Colonel Davis was the model

16:32.709 --> 16:34.275
of an American patriot.

16:34.277 --> 16:35.777
He was a brilliant strategist.

16:35.779 --> 16:41.248
He was respected by his peers
and his fellow officers.

16:41.250 --> 16:44.451
WILDMAN: The colonel faces
a difficult task.

16:44.453 --> 16:47.187
The town of Lewes
has only two cannons

16:47.189 --> 16:48.789
and a limited supply of rifles

16:48.791 --> 16:51.058
with which to fend
off the British,

16:51.060 --> 16:54.529
and the enemy fleet
is just days away.

16:54.531 --> 16:57.531
Destruction was imminent.

16:57.533 --> 17:00.802
WILDMAN: Colonel Davis rallies
as many volunteers as he can

17:00.804 --> 17:03.337
to shore up the town's defenses.

17:03.339 --> 17:05.573
He builds two forts
out of dirt and wood

17:05.575 --> 17:08.710
and strategically
positions his two cannons.

17:08.712 --> 17:12.113
He was gonna protect Lewes
by any means necessary.

17:12.115 --> 17:15.983
♪♪

17:15.985 --> 17:18.419
Finally, the British
fleet arrives,

17:18.421 --> 17:20.621
and on the night of April 6th,

17:23.159 --> 17:25.526
they open fire on Lewes.

17:25.528 --> 17:31.198
♪♪

17:31.200 --> 17:33.834
DiPAOLO:
The town was utter chaos.

17:33.836 --> 17:37.104
Buildings were burning.
Shots were being fired.

17:37.106 --> 17:40.641
Rockets were being fired.
It was a terrifying place to be.

17:40.643 --> 17:43.110
♪♪

17:43.112 --> 17:47.181
WILDMAN: The siege lasts
for more than 22 hours,

17:47.183 --> 17:49.684
and it seems like there's no way
for Colonel Davis

17:49.686 --> 17:51.919
to ward off disaster.

17:51.921 --> 17:55.122
It's only a matter of time
before the British troops land

17:55.124 --> 17:57.724
in Lewes,

17:57.726 --> 18:01.462
but the military man
has a clever ruse in mind.

18:01.464 --> 18:03.397
Out on the Bay,
the British are waiting

18:03.399 --> 18:05.933
until the sun sets
to come ashore,

18:05.935 --> 18:08.135
but as they're about
to make their way to Lewes,

18:08.137 --> 18:12.006
their commander sees
something unexpected --

18:12.008 --> 18:16.410
a vast army of American soldiers
standing on the water's edge,

18:16.412 --> 18:19.814
all equipped with muskets,
ready for battle.

18:19.816 --> 18:22.416
The British were
utterly shocked.

18:22.418 --> 18:25.186
They could not afford
to come ashore now,

18:25.188 --> 18:29.023
so they turned around
and retreated.

18:29.025 --> 18:32.059
So where did this army
suddenly come from?

18:32.061 --> 18:35.863
♪♪

18:37.116 --> 18:39.016
♪♪

18:39.018 --> 18:40.684
It's 1813.

18:40.686 --> 18:42.486
The Royal Navy
has just bombarded

18:42.488 --> 18:45.456
the defenseless American port
of Lewes, Delaware.

18:45.458 --> 18:48.893
A British takeover of the town
seems all but assured,

18:48.895 --> 18:51.428
but as the Redcoats
row toward the shoreline,

18:51.430 --> 18:54.365
they see what appears to be
a large American militia

18:54.367 --> 18:56.634
and beat a hasty retreat,

18:56.636 --> 18:58.636
but what the soldiers
don't realize

18:58.638 --> 19:02.073
is they've fallen
for a corny deception.

19:02.075 --> 19:03.407
♪♪

19:03.409 --> 19:06.610
While the British prepare
to launch their landing party,

19:06.612 --> 19:11.882
Colonel Samuel Davis put
into motion a brilliant scheme.

19:11.884 --> 19:15.353
Davis realized that, if he
could trick the British navy

19:15.355 --> 19:17.921
into thinking there was
a well-equipped army here,

19:17.923 --> 19:20.691
Lewes just might have
a fighting chance.

19:20.693 --> 19:24.228
WILDMAN: The bombardment had
enveloped Lewes in smoke,

19:24.230 --> 19:26.630
and the colonel realized
he could use the haze

19:26.632 --> 19:30.668
to his advantage.

19:30.670 --> 19:33.738
Colonel Davis led a group
of villagers to a field

19:33.740 --> 19:37.975
and instructed each person
to break down a cornstalk.

19:37.977 --> 19:40.278
Then he ordered them
to march to the shore

19:40.280 --> 19:42.279
with the stalks
on their shoulders.

19:42.281 --> 19:47.685
♪♪

19:47.687 --> 19:49.687
DiPAOLO:
This was an ingenious idea.

19:49.689 --> 19:52.823
Through the thick smoke
of combat, to the British,

19:52.825 --> 19:54.625
they look like
a standing army now

19:54.627 --> 19:56.627
and not a ragtag militia.

19:56.629 --> 19:59.363
They were a force
to be reckoned with.

19:59.365 --> 20:01.298
WILDMAN: Believing
the American fighting force

20:01.300 --> 20:03.768
was far stronger
than they had expected,

20:03.770 --> 20:07.304
the British commander signals
his boats to return.

20:07.306 --> 20:11.775
Colonel Davis' gambit works.

20:11.777 --> 20:15.713
His plan had succeeded
beyond his wildest imagination.

20:15.715 --> 20:17.648
He had done the impossible.

20:17.650 --> 20:21.052
He took a group of farm boys
and had held off

20:21.054 --> 20:24.188
and fooled the most powerful
navy in the world.

20:24.190 --> 20:27.858
♪♪

20:27.860 --> 20:30.228
WILDMAN: News of Davis'
deception spreads,

20:30.230 --> 20:33.530
inspiring Americans
to never let up.

20:33.532 --> 20:37.067
Finally, in 1815, the Americans
declare a victory,

20:37.069 --> 20:40.004
once again besting the Crown.

20:40.006 --> 20:43.440
This was a stunning victory
and a huge blow to the British.

20:43.442 --> 20:48.012
♪♪

20:48.014 --> 20:50.815
WILDMAN: Today, a cannonball
from the naval bombardment

20:50.817 --> 20:52.416
remains lodged in the side

20:52.418 --> 20:56.119
of the Lewes Historical
Society in Delaware.

20:56.121 --> 20:59.423
It's a small reminder of
a brilliant piece of deception

20:59.425 --> 21:02.159
that played out
in the fog of war.

21:06.165 --> 21:09.900
Roebling, New Jersey, gets its
name from a former steel mill

21:09.902 --> 21:14.238
founded by famed engineer
John A. Roebling.

21:14.240 --> 21:17.675
The site churned out the beams
of the Empire State Building,

21:17.677 --> 21:20.811
the underpinnings
of the Golden Gate Bridge,

21:20.813 --> 21:25.115
and the elevator cable used
in the Washington Monument.

21:25.117 --> 21:28.085
And celebrating
this manufacturing past

21:28.087 --> 21:30.521
is the Roebling Museum.

21:33.793 --> 21:36.260
The spacious grounds
are strewn with massive

21:36.262 --> 21:38.462
pieces of industrial equipment,

21:38.464 --> 21:42.199
including a 124-ton flywheel

21:42.201 --> 21:45.068
that once powered
the mill itself,

21:45.070 --> 21:48.906
a diesel train engine
used to carry steel,

21:48.908 --> 21:51.809
and a crane way that once
transported scrap metal

21:51.811 --> 21:55.645
and pig iron.

21:55.647 --> 21:57.147
But a much smaller item

21:57.149 --> 22:00.350
can be found inside
the museum's archives.

22:00.352 --> 22:02.419
McMICKENS BLAIR:
This object is incredibly heavy,

22:02.421 --> 22:04.688
more than 50 pounds.

22:04.690 --> 22:08.492
It's covered in a patina
that makes it look sort of like

22:08.494 --> 22:10.194
it's made of clay,

22:10.196 --> 22:14.898
but it's made of steel,
and it's incredibly strong.

22:14.900 --> 22:17.768
♪♪

22:17.770 --> 22:22.239
WILDMAN: This cable is linked
to an iconic Big Apple bridge,

22:22.241 --> 22:24.441
and it recalls
an audacious prank

22:24.443 --> 22:27.545
that plunged the city
into panic.

22:27.547 --> 22:28.979
[ Siren wailing ]
McMICKENS BLAIR:
This is the story of a city

22:28.981 --> 22:32.616
terrorized by
an unusual anniversary gift.

22:36.055 --> 22:38.322
WILDMAN: It's 2014.

22:38.324 --> 22:41.125
Mischa Leinkauf
and Matthias Wermke

22:41.127 --> 22:44.528
are two young
German artists and daredevils.

22:44.530 --> 22:46.731
Rather than galleries
or museums,

22:46.733 --> 22:49.233
they choose to exhibit
their eccentric creations

22:49.235 --> 22:50.968
in public spaces.

22:53.072 --> 22:55.005
Over the course
of their brief career,

22:55.007 --> 22:56.907
the duo has driven a hand cart

22:56.909 --> 22:59.042
through the Berlin
subway system,

22:59.044 --> 23:02.546
dangled on a swing suspended
beneath a skyscraper,

23:02.548 --> 23:05.649
and scaled a residential tower
in Vienna.

23:05.651 --> 23:06.950
They wanted people to think

23:06.952 --> 23:10.220
about the fragility
of public spaces.

23:10.222 --> 23:12.823
This was their life's passion
and work.

23:17.029 --> 23:19.897
WILDMAN: Now the adventurous
artists have their eyes set

23:19.899 --> 23:23.934
on their biggest canvas yet --

23:23.936 --> 23:25.402
the Brooklyn Bridge.

23:25.404 --> 23:27.337
♪♪

23:27.339 --> 23:30.775
Leinkauf and Wermke believe
that the 19th-century edifice

23:30.777 --> 23:34.245
and its German-American
engineer, John A. Roebling,

23:34.247 --> 23:37.047
are vastly underappreciated.

23:37.049 --> 23:38.916
McMICKENS BLAIR:
They were artists

23:38.918 --> 23:41.786
and they were
students of engineering,

23:41.788 --> 23:44.622
so they wanted people
to bring their focus back

23:44.624 --> 23:47.925
to this beautiful,
iconic bridge.

23:47.927 --> 23:53.130
♪♪

23:53.132 --> 23:55.532
WILDMAN: So to thrust
the engineer and his bridge

23:55.534 --> 23:57.001
back into the spotlight,

23:57.003 --> 24:00.270
the artists concoct
a brazen scheme.

24:00.272 --> 24:04.208
On the anniversary
of Roebling's death, July 22nd,

24:04.210 --> 24:07.811
they'll raise two white flags
over the Brooklyn Bridge.

24:07.813 --> 24:10.080
They hope the display
will inspire the public

24:10.082 --> 24:12.883
to look at the monument
in a new way.

24:12.885 --> 24:14.885
McMICKENS BLAIR:
This was a celebration

24:14.887 --> 24:17.154
of the beauty of public space

24:17.156 --> 24:19.390
and the artistry of the bridge.

24:21.961 --> 24:24.027
WILDMAN:
On the evening of July 21st,

24:24.029 --> 24:27.965
Leinkauf and Wermke
climb 275 feet

24:27.967 --> 24:31.068
up one of the bridge's
steel cables.

24:31.070 --> 24:33.137
When they reach the top
of the first tower,

24:33.139 --> 24:38.174
they use aluminum baking pans to
block the bridge's spotlights.

24:38.176 --> 24:40.377
Then, under the cover
of darkness,

24:40.379 --> 24:44.114
they swap the American flag
with a white one

24:44.116 --> 24:47.518
and then repeat the process
on the second tower.

24:47.520 --> 24:51.488
The covert operation
takes a matter of hours.

24:51.490 --> 24:53.023
McMICKENS BLAIR:
I's not an easy thing,

24:53.025 --> 24:55.926
to install flags
on the tops of the towers

24:55.928 --> 24:59.263
at the Brooklyn Bridge,
but it was so well-done,

24:59.265 --> 25:02.933
and it had been done
in such a short time.

25:02.935 --> 25:04.835
WILDMAN: The artists return
to their studio

25:04.837 --> 25:07.671
and eagerly await
the public's reaction.

25:09.275 --> 25:12.943
But the response is unlike
anything they were expecting.

25:12.945 --> 25:14.878
McMICKENS BLAIR:
People were really concerned

25:14.880 --> 25:17.381
that this could be
a part of an upcoming attack.

25:17.383 --> 25:21.719
♪♪

25:23.105 --> 25:24.705
♪♪

25:24.707 --> 25:27.908
It's 2014 in New York City.

25:27.910 --> 25:29.576
Two German artists,

25:29.578 --> 25:32.446
Mischa Leinkauf
and Matthias Wermke,

25:32.448 --> 25:35.182
have just pulled off
an audacious stunt.

25:35.184 --> 25:37.217
They've scaled
the Brooklyn Bridge

25:37.219 --> 25:41.388
and replaced its giant
American flags with white ones.

25:41.390 --> 25:45.325
So what fate would befall
this high-flying duo?

25:45.327 --> 25:46.827
♪♪

25:46.829 --> 25:50.197
On the morning of July 22nd,
New Yorkers awake

25:50.199 --> 25:54.468
and see the unusual flags
flying over the Brooklyn Bridge.

25:54.470 --> 25:55.736
But rather than assume

25:55.738 --> 25:57.871
the display
is a harmless gesture,

25:57.873 --> 26:02.343
most people suspect
something far more nefarious.

26:02.345 --> 26:05.412
McMICKENS BLAIR:
In the wake of 9/11...
[ Siren wailing ]

26:05.414 --> 26:10.350
this was considered
a severe security breach.

26:10.352 --> 26:12.619
People thought it was terrorism.

26:12.621 --> 26:15.689
They were afraid that
there might be another attack

26:15.691 --> 26:16.991
at that point.

26:21.964 --> 26:25.098
WILDMAN: The NYPD launches
an investigation,

26:25.100 --> 26:29.169
and the unexpected display
sparks a media frenzy.

26:29.171 --> 26:31.972
McMICKENS BLAIR: Every reporter
is reporting on this.

26:31.974 --> 26:35.909
Every major news station,
newspaper, magazines

26:35.911 --> 26:38.712
have swarmed on this story,

26:38.714 --> 26:40.781
and they will not let go.

26:44.820 --> 26:46.320
WILDMAN: For their part,

26:46.322 --> 26:49.056
Leinkauf and Wermke
are shocked by the news.

26:49.058 --> 26:52.659
The artists were incredibly
concerned about the panic

26:52.661 --> 26:55.329
that this event had fueled.

26:55.331 --> 27:00.000
They didn't want the artwork to
be mistaken for something else.

27:00.002 --> 27:01.668
WILDMAN: As the scandal grows,

27:01.670 --> 27:06.073
the artists flee to Germany
to avoid prosecution.

27:06.075 --> 27:08.742
Once there, they call
the authorities in New York

27:08.744 --> 27:11.512
and admit they were behind
the stunt.

27:11.514 --> 27:14.581
The public is relieved.

27:14.583 --> 27:16.216
McMICKENS BLAIR:
People are glad to know that

27:16.218 --> 27:18.218
there's nothing in this that,

27:18.220 --> 27:19.953
you know, sort of leads
to terrorism.

27:19.955 --> 27:24.090
All those fears
are all laid to rest.

27:24.092 --> 27:26.226
WILDMAN: The artists return
the American flags

27:26.228 --> 27:28.162
they had confiscated
to the police,

27:28.164 --> 27:29.963
and the Stars and Stripes
once again

27:29.965 --> 27:34.167
fly proudly above one of New
York's most iconic monuments.

27:34.169 --> 27:37.437
For their part, Mischa Leinkauf
and Matthias Wermke

27:37.439 --> 27:40.774
continue their outrageous stunts
to this very day.

27:40.776 --> 27:43.710
♪♪

27:43.712 --> 27:46.546
And this piece of suspension
cable from the Brooklyn Museum

27:46.548 --> 27:47.848
is on display at

27:47.850 --> 27:50.317
the Roebling Museum
in New Jersey.

27:50.319 --> 27:52.519
It recalls
a history-minded stunt

27:52.521 --> 27:55.255
from a pair of
artistic pranksters.

27:55.257 --> 28:01.261
♪♪

28:01.263 --> 28:05.766
An M3 half-track armored truck
from World War II,

28:05.768 --> 28:10.104
a 1947 Sioux helicopter,

28:10.106 --> 28:11.805
and a U.S. Army Jeep

28:11.807 --> 28:16.743
fitted with a massive
105-millimeter rifle

28:16.745 --> 28:20.013
are just some of
the wartime artifacts on display

28:20.015 --> 28:23.717
at the South Carolina
Military Museum.

28:23.719 --> 28:27.120
Located in the city of Columbia,
this institution charts

28:27.122 --> 28:30.758
more than 400 years
of global warfare history.

28:34.897 --> 28:39.266
But one tiny display
speaks to a local conflict.

28:39.268 --> 28:41.235
JEFFCOAT: The objects
are about 2 inches long.

28:41.237 --> 28:44.238
They're sharp on one end
and flat on the other.

28:44.240 --> 28:46.440
The additional objects
are off-white circles

28:46.442 --> 28:48.441
cut with small holes.

28:48.443 --> 28:51.245
They're placed inside of
a light blue felt case.

28:51.247 --> 28:54.881
♪♪

28:54.883 --> 28:56.383
WILDMAN:
These items were salvaged

28:56.385 --> 28:58.719
from a Civil War shipwreck

28:58.721 --> 29:00.120
that some say is linked

29:00.122 --> 29:04.357
to the most famous fictional
Southerner of all time.

29:04.359 --> 29:05.859
JEFFCOAT:
The items are connected

29:05.861 --> 29:07.861
to one of the most unexpected
origin stories

29:07.863 --> 29:09.229
of American literature.

29:09.231 --> 29:15.469
♪♪

29:15.471 --> 29:20.340
WILDMAN: It's 1965
in Charleston, South Carolina.

29:20.342 --> 29:24.344
Edward Lee Spence is a writer
and amateur explorer.

29:24.346 --> 29:26.613
JEFFCOAT: Lee Spence was born
an adventurer.

29:26.615 --> 29:28.481
He is someone who, throughout
his early childhood,

29:28.483 --> 29:32.286
read books about sunken treasure
and about discovered shipwrecks.

29:34.423 --> 29:37.357
WILDMAN: And one lost ship
holds his fascination

29:37.359 --> 29:39.359
more than any other --

29:39.361 --> 29:44.998
a Confederate blockade runner
named the SS<i> Georgiana.</i>

29:45.000 --> 29:48.902
Built in 1863, the vessel
was owned by a wealthy banker

29:48.904 --> 29:51.304
named George Trenholm.

29:51.306 --> 29:53.307
She was supposed to be
the fastest ship

29:53.309 --> 29:57.578
in the Confederate fleet,

29:57.580 --> 29:59.379
but on her maiden voyage,

29:59.381 --> 30:01.782
the<i> Georgiana</i> was attacked
by the Union

30:01.784 --> 30:05.953
and sank somewhere off the coast
of South Carolina.

30:05.955 --> 30:08.922
And despite numerous attempts
to find her,

30:08.924 --> 30:12.726
the exact location of the ship
became lost to history.

30:12.728 --> 30:15.462
JEFFCOAT:
Lee Spence was literally
obsessed with the<i> Georgiana.</i>

30:15.464 --> 30:18.398
He wanted more than anything
to find this mystery ship.

30:18.400 --> 30:21.869
He knew that, even though no one
else had been successful,

30:21.871 --> 30:23.670
that he alone
could actually do it.

30:23.672 --> 30:27.740
♪♪

30:27.742 --> 30:31.177
WILDMAN: After years of studying
maps, historic documents,

30:31.179 --> 30:32.579
and naval records,

30:32.581 --> 30:34.982
Spence has honed in
on what he believes

30:34.984 --> 30:38.418
is the<i> Georgiana's</i>
final resting place.

30:38.420 --> 30:40.220
Sure enough,
when he heads to the site

30:40.222 --> 30:43.223
and dives into the ocean,

30:43.225 --> 30:46.193
he finds a coral-encrusted hull.

30:46.195 --> 30:48.828
It is indeed the<i> Georgiana.</i>

30:48.830 --> 30:50.264
JEFFCOAT: This must have been

30:50.266 --> 30:52.232
a most exhilarating moment
for Spence.

30:52.234 --> 30:54.368
Here he had,
right in front of him,

30:54.370 --> 30:57.237
the wreck of the mystery ship,
the<i> Georgiana.</i>

30:57.239 --> 31:01.375
♪♪

31:01.377 --> 31:05.145
WILDMAN: Spence makes repeated
dives and recovers cannons,

31:05.147 --> 31:09.182
musket balls, and rifles from
the sunken blockade runner.

31:09.184 --> 31:13.553
But curiously, he also finds
more mundane items,

31:13.555 --> 31:17.257
including a box of
tiny sewing pins and buttons,

31:17.259 --> 31:18.658
now on display

31:18.660 --> 31:21.395
at the South Carolina
Military Museum.

31:21.397 --> 31:22.863
JEFFCOAT: They're one
of the few civilian items

31:22.865 --> 31:25.265
recovered in the shipwreck,
and consequently,

31:25.267 --> 31:26.934
they just simply did not fit in

31:26.936 --> 31:30.070
with all this other
valuable cargo.

31:30.072 --> 31:31.805
WILDMAN:
News of Spence's discovery

31:31.807 --> 31:34.841
makes national headlines,

31:34.843 --> 31:37.978
but the remarkable story
doesn't end here.

31:37.980 --> 31:40.947
The discovery of the<i> Georgiana</i>
is about to shed light

31:40.949 --> 31:42.149
on the origins

31:42.151 --> 31:45.018
of one of literature's
most famous characters.

31:45.020 --> 31:46.987
♪♪

31:49.058 --> 31:50.824
♪♪

31:50.826 --> 31:53.159
It's the 1960s.

31:53.161 --> 31:55.629
Amateur explorer
Edward Lee Spence

31:55.631 --> 31:57.063
located the shipwreck

31:57.065 --> 31:59.499
of a long-lost
Confederate blockade runner

31:59.501 --> 32:02.102
named the SS<i> Georgiana.</i>

32:02.104 --> 32:03.436
That's not all.

32:03.438 --> 32:06.506
His marine discovery has also
dredged up the origins

32:06.508 --> 32:09.776
of one of history's most
famous fictional characters.

32:12.047 --> 32:14.981
In 1989, more than 20 years

32:14.983 --> 32:17.818
after he discovered
the SS<i> Georgiana,</i>

32:17.820 --> 32:20.119
Spence decides
to do further research

32:20.121 --> 32:24.357
on the ship's wealthy owner,
George Trenholm.

32:24.359 --> 32:27.427
JEFFCOAT:
Spence began reading court
documents, newspaper accounts.

32:27.429 --> 32:30.564
He even visited Trenholm's
plantation in Georgetown.

32:30.566 --> 32:32.466
WILDMAN:
Trenholm had a reputation

32:32.468 --> 32:34.401
as a charming scoundrel,
a heavy drinker,

32:34.403 --> 32:35.669
and a ladies' man.

32:35.671 --> 32:39.005
♪♪

32:39.007 --> 32:40.540
And as Spence learns more,

32:40.542 --> 32:43.209
he's reminded of one of
the most famous novels

32:43.211 --> 32:46.913
in American literature,

32:46.915 --> 32:49.482
"Gone With the Wind."

32:49.484 --> 32:53.453
Written by Margaret Mitchell
and published in 1936,

32:53.455 --> 32:58.024
the story is set in Georgia
during and after the Civil War.

32:58.026 --> 33:01.428
The book and its 1939
cinematic adaptation

33:01.430 --> 33:05.631
are among the most popular works
of the 20th century.

33:05.633 --> 33:07.834
Its epic tale centers
on a romance

33:07.836 --> 33:11.170
between the headstrong
Southern widow Scarlett O'Hara

33:11.172 --> 33:14.708
and a charismatic rogue
named Rhett Butler.

33:14.710 --> 33:16.710
JEFFCOAT: Rhett Butler is
this literary icon,

33:16.712 --> 33:19.912
this larger-than-life character.

33:19.914 --> 33:22.048
WILDMAN: Spence thinks
the real-life Trenholm

33:22.050 --> 33:23.517
and the fictional Butler

33:23.519 --> 33:27.220
share too much in common
to be coincidence.

33:27.222 --> 33:29.456
JEFFCOAT: Both Trenholm
and his literary counterpart

33:29.458 --> 33:30.857
were known philanderers.

33:30.859 --> 33:32.859
They were heavy gamblers.

33:32.861 --> 33:35.595
WILDMAN: Both men were handsome,
dashing, and wealthy.

33:35.597 --> 33:38.798
Both were successful
blockade runners in the South.

33:38.800 --> 33:42.602
Both were romantically linked to
widows of Confederate soldiers,

33:42.604 --> 33:46.773
and both had daughters
that died young.

33:46.775 --> 33:49.476
But Mitchell, who died in 1949,

33:49.478 --> 33:51.978
had always asserted
that everything in her book

33:51.980 --> 33:55.816
was of her own creation,
perhaps to avoid being sued.

33:55.818 --> 33:57.818
JEFFCOAT:
Margaret Mitchell maintained

33:57.820 --> 33:59.318
that all of the characters
in her novel

33:59.320 --> 34:01.488
"Gone With the Wind"
were completely fictional

34:01.490 --> 34:04.124
and weren't based on living or
historical figures at that time.

34:08.496 --> 34:11.231
WILDMAN: But Spence remembers
an incontrovertible link

34:11.233 --> 34:14.967
between the two characters.

34:14.969 --> 34:16.302
In "Gone With the Wind,"

34:16.304 --> 34:19.239
Rhett Butler attempts to woo
Scarlett O'Hara

34:19.241 --> 34:21.974
by smuggling her
a common household item

34:21.976 --> 34:24.243
that was hard to come by
during the war --

34:24.245 --> 34:27.680
a box of sewing pins
and buttons.

34:27.682 --> 34:32.051
Spence found this exact item
on the SS<i> Georgiana.</i>

34:32.053 --> 34:35.788
In fact, it's the only cargo
that was on the ship

34:35.790 --> 34:39.358
that's specifically mentioned
in the novel.

34:39.360 --> 34:41.127
WILDMAN:
Based on this connection,

34:41.129 --> 34:43.729
Spence concludes that
George Trenholm

34:43.731 --> 34:47.534
is the real-life inspiration
for Rhett Butler.

34:47.536 --> 34:49.669
JEFFCOAT: Scholars today
actually believe

34:49.671 --> 34:51.070
that Spence is right,

34:51.072 --> 34:54.407
that George Trenholm was,
in fact, the real Rhett Butler.

34:54.409 --> 34:56.476
WILDMAN:
Today, these pins and buttons

34:56.478 --> 34:59.746
recovered from the SS<i> Georgiana</i>
are on display

34:59.748 --> 35:02.949
at the South Carolina
Military Museum in Columbia.

35:02.951 --> 35:05.151
They recall a deep-sea discovery

35:05.153 --> 35:08.788
that might just blur the line
between fact and fiction.

35:08.790 --> 35:13.693
♪♪

35:13.695 --> 35:15.095
Easton, Pennsylvania,

35:15.097 --> 35:18.832
is home to the nation's
longest running farmer's market.

35:18.834 --> 35:22.168
First opened in 1752,
Easton Market

35:22.170 --> 35:24.704
is packed with
fresh local produce,

35:24.706 --> 35:28.675
handcrafted goods,
and delectable desserts.

35:28.677 --> 35:31.044
But visitors who are hungry
for knowledge

35:31.046 --> 35:32.913
should head to
a prestigious institution

35:32.915 --> 35:36.182
in nearby
Allentown, Pennsylvania --

35:36.184 --> 35:38.585
Muhlenberg College,
Trexler Library.

35:42.658 --> 35:44.491
The collection includes

35:44.493 --> 35:47.260
a set
of 3,000-year-old tablets

35:47.262 --> 35:51.131
written in an ancient script
known as cuneiform,

35:51.133 --> 35:55.768
an 18th-century poem
illustrated by William Blake,

35:55.770 --> 35:59.939
and an 1843 first edition of
Charles Dickens' classic novel,

35:59.941 --> 36:01.074
"A Christmas Carol."

36:01.076 --> 36:06.646
♪♪

36:06.648 --> 36:08.281
But among
these treasured relics

36:08.283 --> 36:12.051
is one item that was almost lost
to history forever.

36:12.053 --> 36:13.620
FALCIANI: The artifact is about

36:13.622 --> 36:15.355
9 inches high
by 7 inches wide.

36:15.357 --> 36:17.524
The cover has a pebbled texture,

36:17.526 --> 36:21.794
and it's decorated with
ornate gilt filigree design.

36:21.796 --> 36:24.030
This artifact is
over a century old.

36:24.032 --> 36:26.599
♪♪

36:26.601 --> 36:30.303
WILDMAN: This elegant tome
recalls a game of cat-and-mouse

36:30.305 --> 36:33.372
that brought down
a cunning criminal.

36:33.374 --> 36:35.408
FALCIANI: This is the story
of a book bandit

36:35.410 --> 36:37.811
whose meeting with
the law was far overdue.

36:37.813 --> 36:42.649
♪♪

36:42.651 --> 36:47.153
WILDMAN: It's the late 1970s
in St. Louis, Missouri.

36:47.155 --> 36:50.123
James Shinn is a book dealer
who specializes in selling

36:50.125 --> 36:54.460
rare and valuable volumes
to private collectors.

36:54.462 --> 36:58.131
But this salesman has
a dark secret --

36:58.133 --> 37:01.001
he's actually a thief.

37:01.003 --> 37:04.004
Shinn was the cleverest
of criminals.

37:04.006 --> 37:05.604
WILDMAN: Shinn has earned
a fortune

37:05.606 --> 37:07.207
stealing treasured tomes

37:07.209 --> 37:09.676
from university libraries
across the country

37:09.678 --> 37:12.679
and then selling them
to unsuspecting collectors.

37:12.681 --> 37:14.881
FALCIANI: At any given college
or university library,

37:14.883 --> 37:18.484
surprisingly rare materials
are under their care,

37:18.486 --> 37:21.187
sometimes sitting
right out on the shelf.

37:21.189 --> 37:24.491
♪♪

37:24.493 --> 37:25.992
WILDMAN:
The crafty crook has honed

37:25.994 --> 37:28.794
a ruthlessly efficient routine.

37:28.796 --> 37:32.365
First, he scours trade magazines
and library journals

37:32.367 --> 37:35.835
to locate
the most valuable publications.

37:35.837 --> 37:40.139
Then, posing as a professor,
he walks into a library.

37:40.141 --> 37:42.041
Once he's found a book he wants,

37:42.043 --> 37:44.544
he uses a handheld
metal detector

37:44.546 --> 37:47.447
to scan for security devices.

37:47.449 --> 37:50.583
Many libraries use
a magnetic strip

37:50.585 --> 37:52.651
that needs to be
desensitized before a book

37:52.653 --> 37:54.421
can pass through
the security gates

37:54.423 --> 37:56.556
at the door of the library.

37:56.558 --> 37:59.525
WILDMAN: Stealing the book is
as simple as removing the tape,

37:59.527 --> 38:01.661
sticking the book
in his briefcase,

38:01.663 --> 38:04.798
and walking out the front door.

38:04.800 --> 38:06.933
This was not
a small-time operation.

38:06.935 --> 38:08.668
♪♪

38:08.670 --> 38:10.803
WILDMAN: Typically, by the time
anyone realizes

38:10.805 --> 38:12.572
the library has been robbed,

38:12.574 --> 38:14.541
Shinn is long gone.

38:14.543 --> 38:16.809
FALCIANI: He went undetected.

38:16.811 --> 38:19.612
Books often aren't
noticed to be missing

38:19.614 --> 38:22.082
until somebody
has requested it.

38:24.753 --> 38:26.920
WILDMAN:
To prepare the books for resale,

38:26.922 --> 38:30.623
Shinn uses simple tools
like Q-tips and shoe polish

38:30.625 --> 38:33.393
to color match and conceal
any library markings

38:33.395 --> 38:36.396
that would reveal them
as stolen.

38:36.398 --> 38:39.098
But the robberies
haven't gone unnoticed.

38:39.100 --> 38:42.068
Universities are on alert
across the country.

38:42.070 --> 38:45.205
♪♪

38:45.207 --> 38:47.807
And one day,
an alert librarian

38:47.809 --> 38:51.978
spies the thief
pocketing a book.

38:51.980 --> 38:54.614
She calls the police.

38:54.616 --> 38:58.918
By the time they arrive, Shinn
has once again slipped the net.

38:58.920 --> 39:01.388
It seemed like nothing
could stop this book bandit.

39:01.390 --> 39:03.156
♪♪

39:03.158 --> 39:05.024
[Detector whirs]

39:07.045 --> 39:08.778
♪♪

39:08.780 --> 39:10.780
It's 1981.

39:10.782 --> 39:13.983
Notorious book thief James Shinn
has made a fortune

39:13.985 --> 39:17.520
from stealing rare volumes
from college libraries

39:17.522 --> 39:21.124
and selling them
to unsuspecting collectors.

39:21.126 --> 39:26.296
But this literary larcenist
is about to get his comeuppance.

39:26.298 --> 39:27.964
♪♪

39:27.966 --> 39:30.767
December 16, 1981,

39:30.769 --> 39:33.169
Allentown, Pennsylvania.

39:33.171 --> 39:35.438
James Shinn is strolling
through the stacks

39:35.440 --> 39:37.340
at Muhlenberg College Library

39:37.342 --> 39:40.143
when the employees recognize him
from a police sketch

39:40.145 --> 39:42.178
and call security.

39:42.180 --> 39:43.679
FALCIANI: The library staff
at Muhlenberg College

39:43.681 --> 39:45.047
couldn't believe it.

39:45.049 --> 39:47.917
They had just seen James Shinn.

39:47.919 --> 39:50.486
WILDMAN: The librarian detains
Shinn while they wait

39:50.488 --> 39:52.655
for the authorities to arrive,

39:52.657 --> 39:55.658
but Shinn has one last trick
up his sleeve.

39:58.329 --> 40:00.863
He asks the librarian
if he can smoke

40:00.865 --> 40:03.433
and requests an ash tray.

40:03.435 --> 40:08.004
When she looks around,
Shinn runs out the front door.

40:08.006 --> 40:11.574
Once again, when police and FBI
agents arrive on the scene,

40:11.576 --> 40:13.843
Shinn is long gone.

40:13.845 --> 40:16.646
But the wily thief has made
a big mistake.

40:16.648 --> 40:21.384
Agents find he's left behind
a vital clue.

40:21.386 --> 40:23.453
FALCIANI: James Shinn had
dropped a receipt

40:23.455 --> 40:26.523
for the Park Manor Motel
a few miles away.

40:26.525 --> 40:28.358
♪♪

40:28.360 --> 40:32.796
[ Siren wailing ]
WILDMAN: FBI agents rush
to the motel.

40:32.798 --> 40:36.032
Later that night, when Shinn
shows up, they arrest him.

40:38.670 --> 40:42.672
The FBI goes on to recover
hundreds of stolen rare books

40:42.674 --> 40:46.008
from Shinn's stash
in a secret storage locker.

40:46.010 --> 40:50.213
The haul is worth
almost half a million dollars.

40:50.215 --> 40:51.948
This was the real
treasure trove.

40:51.950 --> 40:54.683
These footlockers were filled
with rare books

40:54.685 --> 40:58.321
stolen from libraries
all across the United States.

40:58.323 --> 40:59.622
WILDMAN: Among them

40:59.624 --> 41:03.092
is this 19th-century German book
of poems and folklore,

41:03.094 --> 41:05.361
now on display
at Trexler Library

41:05.363 --> 41:06.763
at Muhlenberg College.

41:09.567 --> 41:12.635
Shinn is convicted of shipping
and receiving stolen goods

41:12.637 --> 41:14.803
across state lines,

41:14.805 --> 41:18.908
and sentenced
to two 10-year terms.

41:18.910 --> 41:22.511
FALCIANI: At the time, this was
the biggest book haul

41:22.513 --> 41:24.314
in U.S. history.

41:24.316 --> 41:26.583
WILDMAN: After the arrest,
the stolen books are returned

41:26.585 --> 41:28.317
to their rightful owners.

41:28.319 --> 41:31.688
♪♪

41:31.690 --> 41:35.525
Today, this rare German book
remains safely in the collection

41:35.527 --> 41:38.928
of Muhlenberg College's
Trexler Library.

41:38.930 --> 41:42.598
It recalls the brazen thief
who closed the book

41:42.600 --> 41:44.067
on his own career.

41:44.069 --> 41:47.203
♪♪

41:47.205 --> 41:49.539
From a brazen book thief

41:49.541 --> 41:52.208
to a box in the woods,

41:52.210 --> 41:54.610
the real Rhett Butler

41:54.612 --> 41:56.646
to the queen of the Nile,

41:56.648 --> 41:58.014
I'm Don Wildman,

41:58.016 --> 42:00.717
and these are the mysteries
at the museum.
